{"title_page": "Simon Wilde", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n[[File:Simon Wilde 20181129.jpg|thumb|Simon Wilde, [[Hatchards]], London, November 2018]]\n'''Simon Wilde''' (born 1960) is an English [[cricket]] journalist and author. He has written for ''[[The Times]]'' and ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' since 1998, and is currently the latter's cricket correspondent.<ref name=\"Indie\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/inside-story-laptop-before-wicket-439841.html] Brief profile published in ''[[The Independent]]''.</ref><ref name=\"Warne\">[https://www.amazon.co.uk/Shane-Warne-Portrait-Flawed-Genius/dp/product-description/0719569419] Author information on Amazon.</ref> Three of his books have been short-listed for the [[William Hill Sports Book of the Year]] award: ''[[Ranji]]: A Genius Rich and Strange'' (1990), ''Letting Rip: The Fast Bowling Threat from Lillee to Waqar'' (1994) and ''[[Shane Warne]]: Portrait of a Flawed Genius'' (2007).\n\nWhen his book on Ranji was reissued in 2005, a reviewer in ''[[The Independent]]'' wrote that it was \"superbly researched and as well written\".<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/sports-books-for-christmas-from-ranji-to-the-romantic-epic-of-winning-the-ashes-519621.html ''The Independent'', 16 December 2005, \"Sports books for Christmas: From Ranji to the romantic epic of winning the Ashes\"]</ref> In reviewing Wilde's book on Warne, Andrew Baker, writing in the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', said that \"Wilde has some pedigree in the quality cricket book market\", and that the book \"is a bit more than sensible and objective. It is entertaining, too...\"<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/2313991/Sportsbooks-Another-spin-on-Warne.html ''Daily Telegraph'', 29 May 2007, \"Sportsbooks: Another spin on Warne\"]</ref> \n \nIn recent years, he has written the annual review of events in world cricket in the previous year for [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]].<ref>E.g. p118 of the 2008 edition.</ref>\n\nHe has three children and lives in [[Hampshire]].\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*''Ranji: A Genius Rich and Strange'', Kingswood, 1990, {{ISBN|978-0-413-63520-4}}\n*''Letting Rip: The Fast Bowling Threat from Lillee to Waqar'', Gollancz/Witherby,  1994, {{ISBN|978-0-85493-242-9}}\n*''Number One: The World's Best Batsmen and Bowlers'', Gollancz, 1998, {{ISBN|978-0-575-06453-9}}\n*''Caught: The Full Story of Corruption in International Cricket'', Aurum Press,  2001, {{ISBN|978-1-85410-816-6}}\n*''Shane Warne: Portrait of a Flawed Genius'', John Murray Publishers, 2007, {{ISBN|978-0-7195-6869-5}}\n*''Ian Botham: The Power and the Glory'', Simon & Schuster UK, 2011, {{ISBN|978-1-84739-798-0}}\n\n'''Note:''' He was also the [[ghost writer]] for [[Graham Thorpe]]'s autobiography: ''Graham Thorpe: Rising from the Ashes'' (2005).<ref name=\"Indie\"/>\n\n== Notes ==\n<references/>\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilde, Simon}}\n[[Category:Cricket historians and writers]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The Times people]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n\n\n{{UK-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n[[File:Simon Wilde 20181129.jpg|thumb|Simon Wilde, [[Hatchards]], London, November 2018]]\n'''Simon Wilde''' (born 1960) is an English [[cricket]] journalist and author. He has written for ''[[The Times]]'' and ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' since 1998, and is currently the latter's cricket correspondent.<ref name=\"Indie\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/inside-story-laptop-before-wicket-439841.html] Brief profile published in ''[[The Independent]]''.</ref><ref name=\"Warne\">[https://www.amazon.co.uk/Shane-Warne-Portrait-Flawed-Genius/dp/product-description/0719569419] Author information on Amazon.</ref> Three of his books have been short-listed for the [[William Hill Sports Book of the Year]] award: ''[[Ranji]]: A Genius Rich and Strange'' (1990), ''Letting Rip: The Fast Bowling Threat from Lillee to Waqar'' (1994) and ''[[Shane Warne]]: Portrait of a Flawed Genius'' (2007).\n\nWhen his book on Ranji was reissued in 2005, a reviewer in ''[[The Independent]]'' wrote that it was \"superbly researched and as well written\".<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/sports-books-for-christmas-from-ranji-to-the-romantic-epic-of-winning-the-ashes-519621.html ''The Independent'', 16 December 2005, \"Sports books for Christmas: From Ranji to the romantic epic of winning the Ashes\"]</ref> In reviewing Wilde's book on Warne, Andrew Baker, writing in the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', said that \"Wilde has some pedigree in the quality cricket book market\", and that the book \"is a bit more than sensible and objective. It is entertaining, too...\"<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/2313991/Sportsbooks-Another-spin-on-Warne.html ''Daily Telegraph'', 29 May 2007, \"Sportsbooks: Another spin on Warne\"]</ref> \n \nIn recent years, he has written the annual review of events in world cricket in the previous year for [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]].<ref>E.g. p118 of the 2008 edition.</ref>\n\nHe has three children and lives in [[Hampshire]].\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*''Ranji: A Genius Rich and Strange'', Kingswood, 1990, {{ISBN|978-0-413-63520-4}}\n*''Letting Rip: The Fast Bowling Threat from Lillee to Waqar'', Gollancz/Witherby,  1994, {{ISBN|978-0-85493-242-9}}\n*''Number One: The World's Best Batsmen and Bowlers'', Gollancz, 1998, {{ISBN|978-0-575-06453-9}}\n*''Caught: The Full Story of Corruption in International Cricket'', Aurum Press,  2001, {{ISBN|978-1-85410-816-6}}\n*''Shane Warne: Portrait of a Flawed Genius'', John Murray Publishers, 2007, {{ISBN|978-0-7195-6869-5}}\n*''Ian Botham: The Power and the Glory'', Simon & Schuster UK, 2011, {{ISBN|978-1-84739-798-0}}\n\n'''Note:''' He was also the [[ghost writer]] for [[Graham Thorpe]]'s autobiography: ''Graham Thorpe: Rising from the Ashes'' (2005).<ref name=\"Indie\"/>\n\n== Notes ==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilde, Simon}}\n[[Category:Cricket historians and writers]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The Times people]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n\n\n{{UK-journalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotes:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simon_Wilde"}
{"title_page": "Simon Ssenkaayi", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|{{orphan|date=March 2019}}{{peacock|date=March 2019}}}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Simon Ssenkaayi\n| image              = File:Simon Ssenkaayi.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Simon giving inspirational speech\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1985|11|22}}\n| birth_place        = [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = \n| years_active       = 2006 \u2014 present\n| nationality        = [[Uganda]]n\n| citizenship        = [[Uganda]]\n| known_for          = [[Inspirational speaker]]\n| website            = {{URL|simonssenkaayi.co.uk}}\n| home_town          = \n}}\n\n'''Simon Ssenkaayi''' (born 22 November 1985) is one of [[Uganda]]\u2019s self-motivated [[Inspirational Speaker|inspirational speaker]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Child |first1=Peace |title=RESPONDING TO EBOLA: PUBLIC HEALTH SOLUTIONS FROM 11 YOUNG PEOPLE |url=https://peacechild.org/responding-to-ebola-public-health-solutions-from-10-young-people/ |website=Peace child}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kingdom |first1=Buganda |title=Nkobazambogo leaders retreat closed |url=http://buganda.or.ug/index.php/news/662-nkobazambogo-leaders-retreat-closed |website=buganda}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=YOUTH IN AGRIBUSINESS: For income generation and job creation |url=https://images.agri-profocus.nl/upload/NATIONAL_YOUTH_SYMPOSIUM1532699334.pdf |website=National Youth Symposium}}</ref> [[author]] and [[motivational speaker]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1512040/-meet-nominees|title=40 under 40: Meet the top nominees|website=www.newvision.co.ug|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>[[motivational speaker|r]], whose message is rooted in his personal experiences and observations. Ssenkaayi is a dynamic personality and highly-sought-after resource in both corporate and non-corporate initiatives, small business owners, non-profit, community leaders and individuals from all walks of life looking to expand opportunity.\n\n==Background==\nSsenkaayi was born in [[Kampala]] [[Uganda]] in 1985 to Stephen Kamya Kiwanuka and Medius Busingye Mirembe.\n\n==Education==\nSsenkaayi attended Vision Nursery School in Sseguku, Standard High School, and Hill College and accomplished both his Bachelor\u2019s Degree in Education (Economics Major) and Master of [[Business Administration]] (MBA \u2013 Marketing Management & Strategy Major) from [[Uganda Martyrs University]]\n\n==Professional life==\nSsenkaayi uses speech to change people\u2019s lives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/artsculture/Reviews/Ssenkaayi-uses-speech-to-change-people-s-lives/691232-5146526-96ut6y/index.html|title=Ssenkaayi uses speech to change people\u2019s lives|website=Daily Monitor|language=en|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref> He inspires his audiences to face their challenges, by weaving his personal life story into the fabric of our everyday lives. His story cautions people not to be complacent, but strive to aim high against all odds, to make a difference not just in their lives, but also make this world a better place for humankind. Against all odds, Ssenkaayi has consistently used his understanding and knowledge beyond \u2018paid-in\u2019 corporate audiences, but also through radio stations inspiring thousands to face their fate, start from where they are and use whatever they can access \u2013 to create their desired kind of life. Ssenkaayi has worked with Youth for Human Rights International (Uganda Chapter), Germany foundation for World Population (Dsw-Bonita), [[Save the children]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Children |first1=Save the |title=Save the Children Uganda |url=https://www.devex.com/organizations/save-the-children-uganda-120561 |website=Devex}}</ref> Uganda, Uganda Red Cross society, [[Luweero]] Youth Section,Young Empowered and Health (Initiative of Uganda Aids Commission) Winsor Consult UK (Uganda Offices),Radio One & [[CBS FM Buganda]] Stations, Ministry of Youth- [[Buganda Kingdom]], Global Empowerment Link (U) Ltd as a founder director, Child & Elderly Support Organization, Royal Treasury (Nkuluze)<ref>{{cite web |last1=trust |first1=nkuluze |title=Corporate and Liaison |url=http://nkuluzetrust.or.ug/departments/corporate-and-liaison |website=http://nkuluzetrust |publisher=nkuluze trust}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Nkuluze |first1=Nkuluze |title=Mwegendereze ababavujjirira ssente okuvvoola Kabaka \u2013 Omuwanika wa Nkuluze |url=http://nkuluzetrust.or.ug/news-and-updates/mwegendereze-ababavujjirira-ssente-okuvvoola-kabaka-%E2%80%93-omuwanika-wa-nkuluze |website=nkuluzetrust}}</ref> and K2 \u2013 Telecom.\n\n==Personal life==\nSsenkaayi is married to Rose Sylvia Nakafu. He has two children.\n\n===Awards===\n\nIn 2013, Simon was selected as one of Africa's top 30 inspirational young people.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Village |first1=Youth |title=Africa\u2019s Top 30 Most Inspirational Young People |url=http://www.youthvillage.co.za/2013/10/africas-top-30-inspirational-young-people/ |website=Youth village}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Simon was ranked among the Sunday Vision\u2019s Top 40 by [[New Vision (newspaper)|New Vision]] one of two main national English-language newspapers in Uganda\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://simonssenkaayi.co.uk Simon Ssenkaayi]\n*[https://disqus.com/by/globalemplink/ Simon on disqus]\n\n__INDEX__\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Ugandan male writers]]\n[[Category:Buganda]]\n[[Category:Ugandan motivational speakers]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kampala]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|{{orphan|date=March 2019}}{{peacock|date=March 2019}}}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Simon Ssenkaayi\n| image              = File:Simon Ssenkaayi.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Simon giving inspirational speech\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1985|11|22}}\n| birth_place        = [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = \n| years_active       = 2006 \u2014 present\n| nationality        = [[Uganda]]n\n| citizenship        = [[Uganda]]\n| known_for          = [[Inspirational speaker]]\n| website            = {{URL|simonssenkaayi.co.uk}}\n| home_town          = \n}}\n\n'''Simon Ssenkaayi''' (born 22 November 1985) is one of [[Uganda]]\u2019s self-motivated [[Inspirational Speaker|inspirational speaker]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Child |first1=Peace |title=RESPONDING TO EBOLA: PUBLIC HEALTH SOLUTIONS FROM 11 YOUNG PEOPLE |url=https://peacechild.org/responding-to-ebola-public-health-solutions-from-10-young-people/ |website=Peace child}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kingdom |first1=Buganda |title=Nkobazambogo leaders retreat closed |url=http://buganda.or.ug/index.php/news/662-nkobazambogo-leaders-retreat-closed |website=buganda}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=YOUTH IN AGRIBUSINESS: For income generation and job creation |url=https://images.agri-profocus.nl/upload/NATIONAL_YOUTH_SYMPOSIUM1532699334.pdf |website=National Youth Symposium}}</ref> [[author]] and [[motivational speaker]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1512040/-meet-nominees|title=40 under 40: Meet the top nominees|website=www.newvision.co.ug|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>[[motivational speaker|r]], whose message is rooted in his personal experiences and observations. Ssenkaayi is a dynamic personality and highly-sought-after resource in both corporate and non-corporate initiatives, small business owners, non-profit, community leaders and individuals from all walks of life looking to expand opportunity.\n\n==Background==\nSsenkaayi was born in [[Kampala]] [[Uganda]] in 1985 to Stephen Kamya Kiwanuka and Medius Busingye Mirembe.\n\n==Education==\nSsenkaayi attended Vision Nursery School in Sseguku, Standard High School, and Hill College and accomplished both his Bachelor\u2019s Degree in Education (Economics Major) and Master of [[Business Administration]] (MBA \u2013 Marketing Management & Strategy Major) from [[Uganda Martyrs University]]\n\n==Professional life==\nSsenkaayi uses speech to change people\u2019s lives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/artsculture/Reviews/Ssenkaayi-uses-speech-to-change-people-s-lives/691232-5146526-96ut6y/index.html|title=Ssenkaayi uses speech to change people\u2019s lives|website=Daily Monitor|language=en|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref> He inspires his audiences to face their challenges, by weaving his personal life story into the fabric of our everyday lives. His story cautions people not to be complacent, but strive to aim high against all odds, to make a difference not just in their lives, but also make this world a better place for humankind. Against all odds, Ssenkaayi has consistently used his understanding and knowledge beyond \u2018paid-in\u2019 corporate audiences, but also through radio stations inspiring thousands to face their fate, start from where they are and use whatever they can access \u2013 to create their desired kind of life. Ssenkaayi has worked with Youth for Human Rights International (Uganda Chapter), Germany foundation for World Population (Dsw-Bonita), [[Save the children]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Children |first1=Save the |title=Save the Children Uganda |url=https://www.devex.com/organizations/save-the-children-uganda-120561 |website=Devex}}</ref> Uganda, Uganda Red Cross society, [[Luweero]] Youth Section,Young Empowered and Health (Initiative of Uganda Aids Commission) Winsor Consult UK (Uganda Offices),Radio One & [[CBS FM Buganda]] Stations, Ministry of Youth- [[Buganda Kingdom]], Global Empowerment Link (U) Ltd as a founder director, Child & Elderly Support Organization, Royal Treasury (Nkuluze)<ref>{{cite web |last1=trust |first1=nkuluze |title=Corporate and Liaison |url=http://nkuluzetrust.or.ug/departments/corporate-and-liaison |website=http://nkuluzetrust |publisher=nkuluze trust}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Nkuluze |first1=Nkuluze |title=Mwegendereze ababavujjirira ssente okuvvoola Kabaka \u2013 Omuwanika wa Nkuluze |url=http://nkuluzetrust.or.ug/news-and-updates/mwegendereze-ababavujjirira-ssente-okuvvoola-kabaka-%E2%80%93-omuwanika-wa-nkuluze |website=nkuluzetrust}}</ref> and K2 \u2013 Telecom.\n\n==Personal life==\nSsenkaayi is married to Rose Sylvia Nakafu. He has two children.\n\n===Awards===\n\nIn 2013, Simon was selected as one of Africa's top 30 inspirational young people.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Village |first1=Youth |title=Africa\u2019s Top 30 Most Inspirational Young People |url=http://www.youthvillage.co.za/2013/10/africas-top-30-inspirational-young-people/ |website=Youth village}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Simon was ranked among the Sunday Vision\u2019s Top 40 by [[New Vision (newspaper)|New Vision]] one of two main national English-language newspapers in Uganda\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://simonssenkaayi.co.uk Simon Ssenkaayi]\n*[https://disqus.com/by/globalemplink/ Simon on disqus]\n\n__INDEX__\n\n[[Category:Ugandan male writers]]\n[[Category:Buganda]]\n[[Category:Ugandan motivational speakers]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kampala]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simon_Ssenkaayi"}
