 of work) || [[Sir Julius Vogel Award]] || Best New Talent || <ref name=\"SJVW 2010\">{{citation | title = Sir Julius Vogel Award Results - 2010 |url=http://www.sffanz.org.nz/sjv/sjvResults-2010.shtml| publisher = SFFANZ | date = | accessdate = 2017-06-21}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20111|[[2011 in literature|2011]]}} || ''Rare Unsigned Copy'' || [[Sir Julius Vogel Award]] || Best Collected Work || <ref name=\"SJV 2011\">{{citation | title = Sir Julius Vogel Award Nominations - 2011 |url=http://www.sffanz.org.nz/sjv/sjvNominations-2011.shtml| publisher = SFFANZ | date = | accessdate = 2017-06-21}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20131|[[2013 in literature|2013]]}} || ''Flight 404'' || [[Ditmar Award]] || Best Novella or Novelette || \n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20132|[[2013 in literature|2013]]}} || ''Light Touch Paper, Stand Clear'' || [[Ditmar Award]] || Best Collected Work || \n|-\n|- style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20133|[[2013 in literature|2013]]}} || ''Flight 404'' || [[Sir Julius Vogel Award]] || Best Novella or Novelette || <ref name=\"SJVW 2013\">{{citation | title = Sir Julius Vogel Award Results - 2013 |url=http://www.sffanz.org.nz/sjv/sjvResults-2013.html| publisher = SFFANZ | date = | accessdate = 2017-06-21}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20134|[[2013 in literature|2013]]}} || ''The Hunt For Red Leicester'' || [[Sir Julius Vogel Award]] || Best Novella or Novelette || <ref name=\"SJV 2013\">{{citation | title = Sir Julius Vogel Award Nominations - 2013 |url=http://www.sffanz.org.nz/sjv/sjvNominations-2013.html| publisher = SFFANZ | date = | accessdate = 2017-06-21}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20141|[[2014 in literature|2014]]}} || ''Difficult Second Album'' || [[Aurealis Award]] || Best Collection || \n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20161|[[2016 in literature|2016]]}} || \"All the Colours of the Tomato\" || [[Aurealis Award]] || Best Science Fiction Novella || \n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20171|[[2017 in literature|2017]]}} || \"All the Colours of the Tomato\" || [[Ditmar Award]] || Best Novella or Novelette || <\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20172|[[2017 in literature|2017]]}} || ''Matters Arising from the Identification of the Body'' || [[Aurealis Award]] || Best Science Fiction Novella || \n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20181|[[2018 in literature|2018]]}} || ''Matters Arising from the Identification of the Body'' || [[Ditmar Award]] || Best Novella or Novelette || \n|-\n|- style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20182|[[2018 in literature|2018]]}} || ''Matters Arising from the Identification of the Body'' || [[Sir Julius Vogel Award]] || Best Novella or Novelette || <ref name=\"SJV 2018\">{{citation | title = Sir Julius Vogel Award Winners - 2018 |url=http://locusmag.com/2018/04/2018-sir-julius-vogel-award-winners/| publisher = Locus Magazine | date = | accessdate = 2018-04-03}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petrie, Simon}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Australian science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Australia-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image        = \n| imagesize    = \n| name         = Simon Petrie\n| caption      = \n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = New Zealand\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| occupation   = \n| nationality  = New Zealand, Australia\n| period       = \n| genre        = [[Speculative fiction]]\n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| children     = Tycho Petrie (Son)\n| relatives    = \n| influences   = \n| influenced   = \n| awards       = '''Sir Julius Vogel Award'''\n| signature    = \n| website      = {{URL|http://simonpetrie.wordpress.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Simon Petrie''' is a [[New Zealand]]-born [[speculative fiction]] writer now based in [[Canberra, Australia]]. He is predominantly recognised as a writer in the science fiction and fantasy genres.<ref>http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/ea.cgi?Simon%20Petrie</ref> Petrie's stories have appeared in a number of Australian publications including Borderlands, [[Aurealis]] and [[Andromeda Spaceways Inflight Magazine]],<ref>http://editormum.livejournal.com/225460.html</ref> in New Zealand publications such as [[Semaphore Magazine]] and several [[Random Static]] anthologies, and in magazines elsewhere in the English-speaking world such as [[Redstone Science Fiction]], [[Murky Depths]] and [[Sybil's Garage]]. He is a former member of the [[Andromeda Spaceways Inflight Magazine]] collective and has edited five issues of the magazine.\n\nPetrie's work has seen several nominations for Australian and New Zealand speculative fiction awards and he has won the [[Sir Julius Vogel Award]] (New Zealand SF Award) three times: in 2010 for Best New Talent,<ref>http://sffanz.sf.org.nz/sjv/sjvResults-2010.shtml</ref> and in 2013 and 2018 for Best Novella or Novelette.<ref>http://www.sffanz.org.nz/sjv/sjvResults-2013.html</ref><ref>http://locusmag.com/2018/04/2018-sir-julius-vogel-award-winners/</ref> He is best known for two series of stories: his 'Gordon Mamon' stories (\"Murder on the Zenith Express\", \"Single Handed\", \"The Fall Guy\", ''The Hunt For Red Leicester'', \"A Night To Remember\", \"Elevator Pitch\" and \"This Guy's The Limit\") centred around the exploits of a space-elevator operative who doubles as a reluctant detective and his 'Titan' stories (''Wide Brown Land'', a collection of eleven short stories, and the novella ''Matters Arising from the Identification of the Body'') exploring human colonization of the Saturnian satellite.\n\n==Bibliography==\n'''Collected short fiction''' \n* ''Rare Unsigned Copy: tales of Rocketry, Ineptitude, and Giant Mutant Vegetables'' (2010, Peggy Bright Books)\n* ''Difficult Second Album: more stories of Xenobiology, Space Elevators, and Bats Out Of Hell'' (2014, Peggy Bright Books)\n* ''Wide Brown Land: stories of Titan'' (2018, Peggy Bright Books)\n* ''80,000 Totally Secure Passwords That No Hacker Would Ever Guess'' (2018)\n* ''Murder on the Zenith Express: the Gordon Mamon collection'' (2018)\n\n'''Novellas'''\n* ''Flight 404''/''The Hunt for Red Leicester'' (2012, Peggy Bright Books)\n* ''[[Matters Arising from the Identification of the Body]]'' (2017, Peggy Bright Books)\n\n'''Anthologies'''\u2014as editor or coeditor\n* ''[[Andromeda Spaceways Inflight Magazine]]'' issues 35, 40, 51, 54, 61 (2008\u20132015, Andromeda Spaceways Publishing Co-operative)\n* ''[[Light Touch Paper, Stand Clear]]'' (2012, Peggy Bright Books, coeditor with Edwina Harvey)\n* ''Next'' (2013, CSFG Publishing, coeditor with Robert Porteous)\n* ''[[Use Only As Directed]]'' (2014, Peggy Bright Books, coeditor with Edwina Harvey)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nIn the following table, entries with a blue background won the award; those with a white background were the nominees on the short-list.\n\n{{color box|#B0C4DE| * |Black}} Award winner<br>\n{{color box|#f9f9f9| * |#f9f9f9}} Nominee on the shortlist\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" width=\"85%\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|-\n! width=\"7%\"|Year\n! width=\"40%\" class=\"unsortable\"|Work\n! width=\"20%\"|Award\n! width=\"29%\"|Category\n! width=\"4%\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20081|[[2008 in literature|2008]]}} || \"Murder on the Zenith Express\" || [[Sir Julius Vogel Award]] || Best Short Story || <ref name=\"SJV 2008\">{{citation | title = Sir Julius Vogel Award Ballot - 2008 |url=http://www.sffanz.org.nz/sjv/sjvBallot-2008.shtml| publisher = SFFANZ